    testimonialName: "Vikram Parmar & Rashmi, Factory Supervisor, Manjalpur",
    testimonialText: "We bought our 2BHK for ₹25 lakhs – almost everything we saved – and had ₹3 lakh for interiors. I worried it would look cheap. The designer understood our dream – they didn't impose minimalism; they used bold turquoise walls, clever storage, smart furniture, and quality tiles strategically placed. When relatives from my village visited, they thought we'd spent triple! My wife cries with joy – she has a proper home after years in quarters. That designer understood that for people like us, interiors isn't luxury – it's dignity and belonging.",
    areaHistory: "Manjalpur's transformation from agricultural land to industrial-residential hub occurred in phases. The 1980s saw GIDC industrial estate establishment, attracting factories and their workers. Initial housing was basic quarters. The 2000s brought developer-driven apartment projects targeting industrial workers – Manjalpur Township (2005) was pivotal, creating community feeling through shared amenities. 2010s saw middle-class expansion – professionals discovered affordable housing with industrial area proximity. Recent years (2020+) have accelerated development with emerging townships and improved infrastructure. Notably, Manjalpur lacks the 'colony' feel of older neighborhoods – it's being built consciously as community, with developers adding schools, parks, and commercial zones.",
