    testimonialText: "My husband and I raised three children in this home, celebrated 40 years of marriage here, and now watch grandchildren play in the same garden where our children played. The structure was getting fragile – plumbing from the 1970s was failing, electrical dangerous, bathrooms outdated. But I couldn't bear to lose this home's soul. The designers performed a miracle – they restored the original wooden ceiling in the living room, preserved the courtyard's function, modernized everything technical invisibly. My granddaughter's friends say it feels like stepping into a beautiful past that still works for today. That's what good heritage design means.",
    areaHistory: "Karelibaug ('garden of plantains' in Gujarati) was developed during the Gaekwad era as Vadodara expanded beyond the old city walls. The 1940s-50s saw construction of substantial bungalows for Vadodara's educated elite – university professors, senior civil servants, successful merchants. The 1960s-70s saw neighborhood maturation with families establishing multi-generational roots. The garden's development as public space in the 1970s transformed Karelibaug into a sought-after residential address. Remarkably, the area maintained its character – no aggressive commercialization, no tower construction that would destroy tree cover. Recent years have seen gentle densification with respectful apartment complexes and renovations. Unlike neighborhoods that transformed dramatically, Karelibaug evolved gradually, maintaining essential character while accommodating growth. This deliberate preservation has become increasingly valuable in fast-changing Vadodara.",
    connectivity: "Positioned at Vadodara's geographic heart, offering access to multiple directions without being in commercial hubbub. Karelibaug Garden acts as transport hub with good bus connectivity. Walking distance to Alkapuri (upscale shopping), Akota (university and culture), and Sayajigunj (CBD). The area's strength is balance – central enough for convenience, quiet enough for peace. No major traffic arteries pass directly through, creating relative quietude despite proximity to busy areas. This connectivity paradox (accessible yet peaceful) is increasingly rare in Indian cities.",
